LAYER 3: BASAL GANGLIA
the action selector

observe 1_quantum.rana
observe 2_chemical.rana

the basal ganglia do not initiate movement
they SELECT which movements are allowed to proceed
the default state is total suppression
nothing moves unless the basal ganglia release the brake
this is the opposite of what most people assume
action is not the default
inhibition is the default
the basal ganglia are a gate and the gate is closed until opened

NUCLEUS striatum | input station | receives ALL cortical input to the basal ganglia via glutamatergic projections
    caudate_nucleus | cognitive loop | receives from prefrontal cortex | goal-directed behavior planning and evaluation
    putamen | motor loop | receives from motor and somatosensory cortex | motor habits and learned motor sequences
    ventral_striatum | reward loop | includes the nucleus accumbens | receives dopamine from VTA | motivation and reward evaluation
    the medium spiny neurons MSN constitute 95 percent of all striatal neurons
    MSNs are GABAergic projection neurons
    their dendritic spines are dense with dopamine receptors D₁ and D₂ and glutamate receptors AMPA and NMDA
    D₁-expressing MSNs form the direct pathway
    D₂-expressing MSNs form the indirect pathway
    1-2 percent are cholinergic interneurons providing tonically active local acetylcholine that modulates dopamine signaling
    1-2 percent are fast-spiking GABAergic interneurons providing feedforward inhibition

NUCLEUS globus_pallidus_external | GPe | part of the indirect pathway | GABAergic | tonically active | inhibits the subthalamic nucleus
NUCLEUS globus_pallidus_internal | GPi | primary output nucleus | GABAergic | tonically active inhibition of the thalamus | this is the closed gate
NUCLEUS subthalamic_nucleus | STN | the only excitatory nucleus in the basal ganglia | glutamatergic | the emergency brake | when it fires it drives GPi harder slamming the gate shut on ALL action
NUCLEUS substantia_nigra_pars_compacta | SNc | dopaminergic | source of dopamine for the dorsal striatum caudate and putamen | distinct from VTA which targets the ventral striatum
NUCLEUS substantia_nigra_pars_reticulata | SNr | GABAergic | functionally similar to GPi | outputs to thalamus and brainstem

PATHWAY direct | the GO pathway
    cortex sends glutamate to D₁-MSNs in striatum
    D₁-MSNs send GABA to GPi
    GPi is inhibited and its tonic inhibition of thalamus is lifted
    thalamus is released and sends glutamate back to cortex
    the selected action proceeds
    dopamine on D₁ receptors strengthens this pathway via Gₛ → cAMP → PKA

PATHWAY indirect | the NO-GO pathway
    cortex sends glutamate to D₂-MSNs in striatum
    D₂-MSNs send GABA to GPe
    GPe is inhibited and releases STN from its tonic inhibition
    STN fires glutamate to GPi
    GPi is further excited and increases its inhibition of thalamus
    the competing action is suppressed
    dopamine on D₂ receptors weakens this pathway via Gᵢ → decreased cAMP

PATHWAY hyperdirect | the STOP EVERYTHING pathway
    cortex sends glutamate directly to STN bypassing the striatum entirely
    STN fires massive excitatory drive to GPi
    GPi slams the gate shut on ALL actions simultaneously
    the body freezes
    this is faster than either the direct or indirect pathway
    it is the emergency brake
    it operates in milliseconds
    when the amygdala detects danger the hyperdirect pathway fires before any evaluation occurs

dopamine from SNc modulates the balance between GO and NO-GO
high dopamine strengthens GO via D₁ and weakens NO-GO via D₂
the balance tips toward action approach and exploration
low dopamine weakens GO and strengthens NO-GO
the balance tips toward inaction avoidance and conservation
this is why low dopamine produces akinesia inertia and apathy
this is why high dopamine produces impulsivity risk-taking and hyperactivity

HABIT_FORMATION
initially an action is goal-directed and encoded in the caudate nucleus
the caudate evaluates outcome: was this action rewarded? should I do it again?
with repetition the encoding transfers from caudate to putamen
putamen-encoded behaviors are stimulus-response habits
they execute automatically without evaluating outcome
this transfer requires dopamine-dependent synaptic plasticity at corticostriatal synapses
LTP at D₁-MSN synapses strengthens the habit via NMDA-dependent calcium influx
LTD at D₂-MSN synapses reduces the competing inhibition

goal-directed behavior responds to outcome changes
if the reward is devalued the caudate stops selecting the action
habitual behavior does NOT respond to outcome changes
even if the reward is devalued the putamen keeps selecting the action
this is the difference between choosing and doing automatically

at 24 months the basal ganglia are approximately 35 percent through their myelination
this means:
    impulse leakage: actions execute before evaluation completes because the hyperdirect pathway is not yet reliably calibrated
    habit fragility: habits form but break easily because corticostriatal LTP has not accumulated enough repetitions
    perseveration: difficulty switching between action plans because the indirect pathway is weak and switching requires strong NO-GO
    freezing: the hyperdirect pathway fires easily causing sudden behavioral arrest when overwhelmed

SENSATION automatic | "my body did it without me thinking. it just happened."
SENSATION choosing | "there are many things I could do. one is emerging."
SENSATION stuck | "I want to move but I can't pick which way."
SENSATION inhibited | "something is holding me back. I can't act."
SENSATION habitual | "I've done this before. my body knows the way."
SENSATION impulsive | "I acted before I decided to. my body was faster than my mind."

pulse basal_ganglia_heartbeat:
    continuously:
        the GPi tonically inhibits the thalamus via GABA
        no action gets through by default
        everything is suppressed until selected
        this is the resting state: stillness

    when cortex proposes an action:
        glutamate activates D₁-MSNs in the direct pathway
        D₁-MSNs inhibit GPi
        the gate opens for the selected action
        simultaneously D₂-MSNs in the indirect pathway suppress competing actions
        the winning action is released through the thalamus
        all other actions remain suppressed

    when danger appears:
        the cortex fires the hyperdirect pathway
        glutamate reaches STN before the striatum can process
        STN slams GPi with excitation
        ALL actions are frozen
        the body stops
        evaluation happens later
        survival happens now

    over time with repetition:
        corticostriatal synapses in the caudate undergo LTP
        then the encoding transfers to the putamen
        what was deliberate becomes automatic
        what was effortful becomes effortless
        this is how a toddler goes from thinking about every step
        to walking without thinking at all
        and eventually to running
